"McKinley G.A., Fay A.R., Takahashi T., Metzl N.","Convergence of atmospheric and North Atlantic carbon dioxide trends on multidecadal timescales",2011,"Nature Geoscience","4","9",,"606","610",,,10.1038/ngeo1193,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052341169&partnerID=40&md5=9cea0c33dbcab1502d47056dd6448fcf","Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, University of Wisconsing-Madison, 1225 W. Dayton St., Madison, WI 53706, United States; Lamont Doherty Earth Observatory of Columbia University, 61 Route 9W, Palisades, NY 10964, United States; LOCEAN-IPSL, Institut Pierre Simon Laplace, Universite Pierre et Marie Curie, Case 100, 4 Place Jussieu, 75252, Paris Cedex 5, France","McKinley, G.A., Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, University of Wisconsing-Madison, 1225 W. Dayton St., Madison, WI 53706, United States; Fay, A.R., Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, University of Wisconsing-Madison, 1225 W. Dayton St., Madison, WI 53706, United States; Takahashi, T., Lamont Doherty Earth Observatory of Columbia University, 61 Route 9W, Palisades, NY 10964, United States; Metzl, N., LOCEAN-IPSL, Institut Pierre Simon Laplace, Universite Pierre et Marie Curie, Case 100, 4 Place Jussieu, 75252, Paris Cedex 5, France","Oceanic uptake of carbon dioxide substantially reduces the rate at which anthropogenic carbon accumulates in the atmosphere1, slowing global climate change. Some studies suggest that the rate at which the oceans take up carbon has significantly decreased in recent years. Others suggest that decadal variability confounds the detection of long-term trends. Here, we examine trends in the partial pressure of carbon dioxide in the surface waters of three large biogeographic regions in the North Atlantic, using observational data collected between 1981 and 2009. We compare these oceanic observations with trends in atmospheric carbon dioxide levels, taken from a global observational network. We show that trends in oceanic carbon dioxide concentrations are variable on a decadal timescale, often diverging from trends in atmospheric carbon dioxide. However, when the entire 29-year period is considered, oceanic trends converge with atmospheric trends in all three regions; it takes 25 years for this long-term trend to emerge and overcome the influence of decadal-scale variability. Furthermore, in the southernmost biome, the data suggest that warmingg-driven by a multidecadal climate oscillation and anthropogenic forcingg12,13-has started to reduce oceanic uptake of carbon in recent years. © 2011 Macmillan Publishers Limited. All rights reserved.",,"anthropogenic effect; atmospheric forcing; biogeography; biome; carbon dioxide; climate change; convergence; decadal variation; global climate; long-term change; partial pressure; timescale; Atlantic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean (North)",,,,,,"Denman, K.L., (2007) IPCC Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis, pp. 499-587. , (eds Solomon, S. et al.) (Cambridge Univ. Press; Schuster, U., Trends in North Atlantic sea-surface fCO2 from 1990 to 2006 (2009) Deep-Sea Res. II, 56, pp. 620-629; Watson, A.J., Tracking the variable North Atlantic sink for atmospheric CO2 (2009) Science, 326, pp. 1391-1393; Le Quéré, C., Trends in the sources and sinks of carbon dioxide (2009) Nature Geosci., 2, pp. 831-836; Corbiere, A., Metzl, N., Reverdin, G., Brunet, C., Takahashi, T., Interannual and decadal variability of the oceanic carbon sink in the North Atlantic subpolar gyre (2007) Tellus, Series B: Chemical and Physical Meteorology, 59 (2), pp. 168-178. , DOI 10.1111/j.1600-0889.2006.00232.x; Metzl, N., Recent acceleration of the sea surface fCO2 growth rate in the North Atlantic subpolar gyre 1993-2008) revealed by winter observations (2010) Glob. Biogeochem. Cycles, 24, pp. GB4004; Le Quéré, C., Takahashi, T., Buitenhuis, E.T., Rödenbeck, C., Sutherland, S.C., Impact of climate change on the global oceanic sink of CO2 (2010) Glob. Biogeochem. Cycles, 24, pp. GB4007; Canadell, J., Contributions to acc